= section "Introduction to 'aktēb Verbs" do
  %p <i>'Aktēb</i> (Active Scale III) is commonly known as the “causative” stem. Its most common function, not surprisingly, is causative, and it typically converts transitive <i>katab</i> verbs into ditransitive ones: #{t "ακτήβ", "'aktēb"} “dictate [something to someone]” (lit. 'cause to write'), #{t "αηακήλ", "'ahakēl"} “feed [something to someone]” (lit. 'cause to eat'). It can have a causative meaning on verbs whose base form is intransitive, but this is less common: #{t "ασκήβ", "'askēb"} “lay down” (lit. 'cause to lie down'). For some verbs, it may also have a factitive meaning (“to have something done by somone”), as in #{t "ου αμήτετ", "'ū 'amētet"} “I had him killed” (from *mūt “die”), or an assistive meaning, as in #{t "ασλήτ", "'aslēt"} “help someone win” (from *slāth “win, prevail over”).
  %p <i>'Aktēb</i> is distinguished by its prefixed /ʔ/, although in some forms this elides and may change the quality of the vowels around it. In Semitic studies this form is often known as the '-Stem or Š-Stem (the latter for historical reasons).

= section "Triconsonantal Roots and 'aktēb" do
  = section "The Present Tense" do
    %p The <i>'aktēb</i> present tense is quite easy to form. It simply requires adding personal prefixes and suffixes to the stems #{template "*-C1C2ēC3"} (when no suffix is present) or #{template "*-C1C2eC3-"} (when there is a suffix present). The prefix vowel is always /ɑː/, the product of the original prefix vowels merging together with the causative *'a- prefix.
    - alashian = %w(ωκτήβ τωκτήβ τωκτεβεί ιωκτήβ ιωκτεβεί νωκτεβού τωκτεβού τωκτεβού ιωκτεβού ιωκτεβού)
    - latin = %w('āktēb tāktēb tāktebī yāktēb yāktebī nāktebū tāktebū tāktebū yāktebū yāktebū)
    = render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Present Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'aktēb", :eng => "dictate" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Preterite Tense" do
    %p The preterite tense is formed regularly by adding preterite suffixes to the stem #{template "*'aC1C2ēC3-"}. #{template "C3"} lenition may take place in the second person.
    - alashian = %w(ακτήβετ ακτήв̄τα ακτήв̄σ̄ε ακτήβ ακτηβώ ακτηβνώ ακτήв̄τυν ακτήв̄σ̄ιν ακτηβού ακτηβού)
    - latin = %w('aktēbet 'aktēvta 'aktēvše 'aktēb 'aktēbā 'aktēbnā 'aktēvtun 'aktēvšin 'aktēbū 'aktēbū)
    = render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Preterite Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'aktēb", :eng => "dictate" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Imperfect Tense" do
    %p The imperfect tense is formed by adding the imperfect suffixes to the stem #{template "*'aC1C2ieC3-"}. #{template "C3"} lenition may take place in the first and second person forms.
    - alashian = %w(ακτιήв̄ ακτιήв̄ετ ακτιήв̄ες̄ ακτιήβ ακτιηβώ ακτιήв̄εν ακτιήв̄τυν ακτιήв̄σ̄ιν ακτιηβού ακτιηβού)
    - latin = %w('aktiev 'aktievet 'aktieveš 'aktieb 'aktiebā 'aktieven 'aktievtun 'aktievšin 'aktiebū 'aktiebū)
    = render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Imperfect Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'aktēb", :eng => "dictate" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Perfective Subjunctive Tense" do
    %p The perfective subjunctive is formed by adding a special set of prefixes to the stem #{template "*-C1C2eC3"}. The prefixes used in <i>'aktēb</i> are *vā- in the first person singular, *vanā- in the first person plural, *vatā- in the second person, and *vyā- in the third person.
    - alashian = %w(в̄ώκτεβ в̄ατώκτεβ в̄ιώκτεβ в̄ανώκτεβ в̄ατώκτεβ в̄ιώκτεβ)
    - latin = %w(vākteb vatākteb vyākteb vanākteb vatākteb vyākteb)
    = render 'subjunctive_table', :title => "Scale III Perfective Subjunctive", :verb => { :ala => "'aktēb", :eng => "dictate" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Imperative" do
    %p The imperative usually takes the form #{template "*'aC1C2ēC3"} in the masculine singular, and #{template "*'aC1C2eC3-"} + suffixes in the feminine singular and plural.
    - alashian = %w(ακτήβ ακτεβεί ακτεβού ακτεβού)
    - latin = %w('aktēb 'aktebī 'aktebū 'aktebū)
    = render 'imperative_table', :title => "Scale III Imperative", :verb => { :ala => "'aktēb", :eng => "dictate" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
    %p However, a handful of very common verbs preserve a different, older pattern. They form their imperative stems with the patterns #{template "*'isC1eC2ēC3"} (masculine singular) and #{template "*'isC1eC2C3-"} (feminine singular and plural). This is especially common, for instance, with verbs of position such as #{t "ασκήβ", "'askēb"} “lay down” (root *skīb “lie down”):
    - alashian = %w(ισσεκήβ ισσεκβεί ισσεκβού ισσεκβού)
    - latin = %w('issekēb 'issekbī 'issekbū 'issekbū)
    = render 'imperative_table', :title => "Scale III Imperative", :verb => { :ala => "'askēb", :eng => "lay down" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "Deverbatives" do
    %p The infinitive is formed using the pattern #{template "*māC1C2ēC3"} and the participle using #{template "māC1C2iC3"}.
    - alashian = [ { :name => "Infinitive", :ala => "μωκτήβ", :lat => "māktēb", :meaning => "dictate" },
                   { :name => "Active Part.", :ala => "μώκτιβ", :lat => "māktib", :meaning => "dictating" } ]

= section "Biconsonantal Roots and 'aktēb" do
  %p Biconsonantal roots lose their internal vowel in <i>'aktēb</i> and replace it with /ɛː/, gained by analogy with other <i>'aktēb</i> verbs. This #{template "*-C1ēC2-"} stem remains intact in all forms, except in the imperfect, which uses the stem #{template "*-C1ieC2-"}, and the active participle, which uses #{template "*-C1ūC2-"} instead#{footnote}.
  %p The root *sāl “ask” may serve as an example, becoming <i>'asēl</i> “lend” in <i>'aktēb</i>.#{footnote}
  - alashian = { :present     => %w(ωσήλ τωσήλ τωσηλεί ιωσήλ ιωσηλεί νωσηλού τωσηλού τωσηλού ιωσηλού),
                 :preterite   => %w(ασήλετ ασήλτα ασήλσ̄ε ασήλ ασηλώ ασηλνώ ασήλτυν ασήλσ̄ιν ασηλού),
                 :imperfect   => %w(ασιήλ ασιήλετ ασιήλες̄ ασιήλ ασιηλώ ασιήλεν ασιήλτυν ασιήλσ̄ιν ασιηλού),
                 :subjunctive => %w(в̄ωσήλ в̄ατωσήλ в̄ατωσήλ в̄ιωσήλ в̄ιωσήλ в̄ανωσήλ в̄ατωσήλ в̄ατωσήλ в̄ιωσήλ),
                 :imperative  => %w(ασήλ ασηλεί ασηλού),
                 :infinitive  => "μωσήλ",
                 :participle  => "μωσούλ" }
  - latin = { :present     => %w('āsēl tāsēl tāsēlī yāsēl yāsēlī nāsēlū tāsēlū tāsēlū yāsēlū),
              :preterite   => %w('asēlet 'asēlta 'asēlše 'asēl 'asēlā 'asēlnā 'asēltun 'asēlšin 'asēlū),
              :imperfect   => %w('asiel 'asielet 'asieleš 'asiel 'asielā 'asielen 'asieltun 'asielšin 'asielū),
              :subjunctive => %w(vāsēl vatāsēl vatāsēl vyāsēl vyāsēl vanāsēl vatāsēl vatāsēl vyāsēl),
              :imperative  => %w('asēl 'asēlī 'asēlū),
              :infinitive  => "māsēl",
              :participle  => "māsūl" }
  = render 'full_conjugation_table', :title => "Scale III Conjugation", :verb => { :ala => "'asēl", :eng => "lend" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin 
  %p The special s-imperative exists as well, as seen with the verb #{t "ακκήν", "'akhēn"} “raise, set up” (*khūn “get up”):
  - alashian = %w(ισκήν ισκηνεί ισκηνού ισκηνού)
  - latin = %w('iskēn 'iskēnī 'iskēnū 'iskēnū)
  = render 'imperative_table', :title => "Scale III Imperative", :verb => { :ala => "'akhēn", :eng => "raise" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

= section "Quadriconsonantal Roots and 'aktēb" do
  %p Quadriconsonantal roots are allowed in <i>'aktēb</i>, although they naturally have a different stem structure. The verb #{t "ακελκήλ", "'akelkēl"} “ring (tr)” (root *kalkēl “ring (intr)”) will demonstrate.
  %p In the present tense, the stem alternates between #{template "*-C1eC2C3ēC4"} when there is no suffix and #{template "*-C1eC2C3eC4-"} when there is a suffix:
  - alashian = %w(ωκελκήλ τωκελκήλ τωκελκελεί ιωκελκήλ ιωκελκελεί νωκελκελού τωκελκελού τωκελκελού ιωκελκελού ιωκελκελού)
  - latin = %w('ākelkēl tākelkēl tākelkelī yākelkēl yākelkelī nākelkelū tākelkelū tākelkelū yākelkelū yākelkelū)
  = render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Present Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'akelkēl", :eng => "ring (tr)" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
  %p The preterite is based on the static stem #{template "*'aC1eC2C3ēC4-"}:
  - alashian = %w(ακελκήλετ ακελκήλτα ακελκήλσ̄ε ακελκήλ ακελκηλώ ακελκηλνώ ακελκήλτυν ακελκήλσ̄ιν ακελκηλού ακελκηλού)
  - latin = %w('akelkēlet 'akelkēlta 'akelkēlše 'akelkēl 'akelkēlā 'akelkēlnā 'akelkēltun 'akelkēlšin 'akelkēlū 'akelkēlū)
  = render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Preterite Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'akelkēl", :eng => "ring (tr)" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
  %p The imperfect tense uses the stem #{template "*'aC1eC2C3ieC4-"}:
  - alashian = %w(ακελκιήλ ακελκιήλετ ακελκιήλες̄ ακελκιήλ ακελκιηλώ ακελκιήλεν ακελκιήλτυν ακελκιήλσ̄ιν ακελκιηλού ακελκιηλού)
  - latin = %w('akelkiel 'akelkielet 'akelkieleš 'akelkiel 'akelkielā 'akelkielen 'akelkieltun 'akelkielšin 'akelkielū 'akelkielū)
  = render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Imperfect Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'akelkēl", :eng => "ring (tr)" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
  %p The perfective subjunctive uses the stem #{template "*-C1eC2C3eC4"}:
  - alashian = %w(в̄ώκελκελ в̄ατώκελκελ в̄ιώκελκελ в̄ανώκελκελ в̄ατώκελκελ в̄ιώκελκελ)
  - latin = %w(vākelkel vatākelkel vyākelkel vanākelkel vatākelkel vyākelkel)
  = render 'subjunctive_table', :title => "Scale III Perfective Subjunctive", :verb => { :ala => "'akelkēl", :eng => "ring (tr)" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
  %p The imperative stem is #{template "*'aC1eC2C3ēC4"} in the masculine singular and #{template "*'aC1eC2C3eC4-"} in the feminine singular and plural. There are no quadriconsonantal roots with s-imperatives.
  - alashian = %w(ακελκήλ ακελκελεί ακελκελού ακελκελού)
  - latin = %w('akelkēl 'akelkelī 'akelkelū 'akelkelū)
  = render 'imperative_table', :title => "Scale III Imperative", :verb => { :ala => "'akelkēl", :eng => "ring (tr)" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
  %p The infinitive of quadriconsonantal roots uses the pattern #{template "*māC1eC2C3ēC4"} and the active participle uses #{template "*māC1aC2C3iC4"}:
  - alashian = [ { :name => "Infinitive", :ala => "μωκελκήλ", :lat => "mākelkēl", :meaning => "ring" },
                 { :name => "Active Part.", :ala => "μώκαλκιλ", :lat => "mākalkil", :meaning => "ringing" } ]
  = render 'deverbative_table', :title => "Scale III Deverbatives", :verb => { :ala => "'akelkēl", :eng => "ring (tr)" }, :forms => alashian

= section "Geminate Roots and 'aktēb" do
  %p The behavior of geminate roots can be summarized with a simple rule: if the stem is followed by a suffix beginning with a vowel, it follows a biconsonantal pattern with gemination; otherwise (when word-final or followed by a consonant-initial suffix), it follows a triconsonantal pattern. The verb #{t "ασβήβ", "'asbēb"} “cause, bring about” (root *sabb “turn”) will demonstrate:
  - alashian = { :present     => %w(ωσβήβ τωσβήβ τωσηββεί ιωσβήβ ιωσηββεί νωσηββού τωσηββού τωσηββού ιωσηλού),
                 :preterite   => %w(ασήββετ ασβήв̄τα ασβήв̄σ̄ε ασβήβ ασηββώ ασβηβνώ ασβήв̄τυν ασβήв̄σ̄ιν ασηββού),
                 :imperfect   => %w(ασβιήв̄ ασιήв̄в̄ετ ασιήв̄в̄ες̄ ασβιήβ ασιηββώ ασιήв̄в̄εν ασβιήв̄τυν ασβιήв̄σ̄ιν ασιηββού),
                 :subjunctive => %w(в̄ώσβεβ в̄ατώσβεβ в̄ατώσβεβ в̄ιώσβεβ в̄ιώσβεβ в̄ανώσβεβ в̄ατώσβεβ в̄ατώσβεβ в̄ιώσβεβ),
                 :imperative  => %w(ασβήβ ασηββεί ασηββού),
                 :infinitive  => "μωσβήβ",
                 :participle  => "μώσβιβ" }
  - latin = { :present     => %w('āsbēb tāsbēb tāsēbbī yāsbēb yāsēbbī nāsēbbū tāsēbbū tāsēbbū yāsēbbū),
              :preterite   => %w('asēbbet 'asbēvta 'asbēvše 'asbēb 'asēbbā 'asbēbnā 'asbēvtun 'asbēvšin 'asēbbū),
              :imperfect   => %w('asbiev 'asievvet 'asievveš 'asbieb 'asiebbā 'asievven 'asbievtun 'asbievšin 'asiebbū),
              :subjunctive => %w(vāsbeb vatāsbeb vatāsbeb vyāsbeb vyāsbeb vanāsbeb vatāsbeb vatāsbeb vyāsbeb),
              :imperative  => %w('asbēb 'asēbbī 'asēbbū),
              :infinitive  => "māsbēb",
              :participle  => "māsbib" }
  = render 'full_conjugation_table', :title => "Scale III Conjugation", :verb => { :ala => "'asbēb", :eng => "cause" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

= section "Introduction to 'ennuktāb Verbs" do
  %p The passive counterpart of <i>'aktēb</i> is <i>'ennuktāb</i>. It contains the internal vowel pattern u-a commonly seen in passive forms. It later acquired a prefixed n- by analogy with the passive scale I <i>nuktāb</i>. To make the initial *n' cluster more pronounceable, an epenthetic /e/ was introduced at the beginning of the word. Over time the original glottal stop marking the causative assimilated into the /n/. The evolution of this form was thus roughly: <i>'uktāb</i> → <i>n'uktāb</i> → <i>'en'uktāb</i> → <i>'ennuktāb</i>.
  %p The noun functioning as the direct object in <i>'aktēb</i> is promoted to subject in <i>'ennuktāb</i>. Therefore, the actual verb <i>'ennuktāb</i> means “be dictated” and takes an animate object (e.g., “he was dictated a letter”).

= section "Triconsonantal Roots and 'ennuktāb" do
  = section "The Present Tense" do
    %p The present tense forms are created regularly by adding standard prefixes and suffixes to the stems #{template "*-nnuC1C2āC3"} (when no suffix is present) or #{template "*-nnuC1C2aC3-"} (when there is a suffix present). All prefixes have the vowel /i/ other than the first person singular, which has /a/.
    - alashian = %w(αννυκτώβ τιννυκτώβ τιννυκταβεί ιννυκτώβ ιννυκταβεί νιννυκταβού τιννυκταβού τιννυκταβού ιννυκταβού ιννυκταβού)
    - latin = %w('annuktāb tinnuktāb tinnuktabī yinnuktāb yinnuktabī ninnuktabū tinnuktabū tinnuktabū yinnuktabū yinnuktabū)
    = render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Present Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'ennuktāb", :eng => "be dictated" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Preterite Tense" do
    %p The preterite tense features regular preterite suffixes added to the stem #{template "*'ennuC1C2āC3-"}:
    - alashian = %w(εννυκτώβετ εννυκτώв̄τα εννυκτώв̄σ̄ε εννυκτώβ εννυκτωβώ εννυκτωβνώ εννυκτώв̄τυν εννυκτώв̄σ̄ιν εννυκτωβού εννυκτωβού)
    - latin = %w('ennuktābet 'ennuktāvta 'ennuktāvše 'ennuktāb 'ennuktābā 'ennuktābnā 'ennuktāvtun 'ennuktāvšin 'ennuktābū 'ennuktābū)
    = render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Preterite Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'ennuktāb", :eng => "be dictated" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Imperfect Tense" do
    %p The imperfect tense is based on the stem #{template "*'ennuC1C2uoC3-"} and uses suffixes containing the vowel /a/:
    - alashian = %w(εννυκτυώв̄ εννυκτυώв̄ατ εννυκτυώв̄ας̄ εννυκτυώβ εννυκτυωβώ εννυκτυώв̄αν εννυκτυώв̄τυν εννυκτυώв̄σ̄ιν εννυκτυωβού εννυκτυωβού)
    - latin = %w('ennuktuov 'ennuktuovat 'ennuktuovaš 'ennuktuob 'ennuktuobā 'ennuktuovan 'ennuktuovtun 'ennuktuovšin 'ennuktuobū 'ennuktuobū)
    = render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Imperfect Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'ennuktāb", :eng => "be dictated" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Perfective Subjunctive Tense" do
    %p The perfective subjunctive is formed by adding a special set of prefixes to the stem *-nnuktab. In the first person singular the prefix is *va-, in the first person plural *vani-, in the second person *vati-, and in the third person *vē-.
    - alashian = %w(в̄άννυκταβ в̄ατίννυκταβ в̄ήννυκταβ в̄ανίννυκταβ в̄ατίννυκταβ в̄ήννυκταβ)
    - latin = %w(vannuktab vatinnuktab vēnnuktab vaninnuktab vatinnuktab vēnnuktab)
    = render 'subjunctive_table', :title => "Scale III Perfective Subjunctive", :verb => { :ala => "'ennuktāb", :eng => "be dictated" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Imperative" do
    %p No imperative exists for <i>'ennuktāb</i>.

  = section "Deverbatives" do
    %p The infinitive uses the pattern #{template "*mannuC1C2āC3"} and the passive participles use #{template "*munnaC1C2aC3"}.
    - alashian = [ { :name => "Infinitive", :ala => "μαννυκτώβ", :lat => "mannuktāb", :meaning => "be dictated" },
                   { :name => "Passive Part.", :ala => "μύννακταβ", :lat => "munnaktab", :meaning => "dictated" } ]
    = render 'deverbative_table', :title => "Scale III Deverbatives", :verb => { :ala => "'ennuktāb", :eng => "be dictated" }, :forms => alashian

= section "Biconsonantal Roots and 'ennuktāb" do
  %p Biconsonantal verbs lose their internal vowel, replacing it with /ɑː/ in the present, preterite, perfective subjunctive, and infinitive, /uo/ in the imperfect, and /uː/ in the passive participle. Demonstrated with #{t "εννυσώλ", "'ennusāl"} “be lent”:
  - alashian = { :present     => %w(αννυσώλ τιννυσώλ τιννυσωλεί ιννυσώλ ιννυσωλεί νιννυσωλού τιννυσωλού τιννυσωλού ιννυσωλού),
                 :preterite   => %w(εννυσώλετ εννυσώλτα εννυσώλσ̄ε εννυσώλ εννυσωλώ εννυσωλνώ εννυσώλτυν εννυσώλσ̄ιν εννυσωλού),
                 :imperfect   => %w(εννυσυώλ εννυσυώλατ εννυσυώλας̄ εννυσυώλ εννυσυωλώ εννυσυώλαν εννυσυώλτυν εννυσυώλσ̄ιν εννυσυωλού),
                 :subjunctive => %w(в̄αννυσώλ в̄ατιννυσώλ в̄ατιννυσώλ в̄ηννυσώλ в̄ηννυσώλ в̄ανιννυσώλ в̄ατιννυσώλ в̄ατιννυσώλ в̄ηννυσώλ),
                 :imperative  => nil,
                 :infinitive  => "μαννυσώλ",
                 :participle  => "μυννασούλ" }
  - latin = { :present     => %w('annusāl tinnusāl tinnusālī yinnusāl yinnusālī ninnusālū tinnusālū tinnusālū yinnusālū),
              :preterite   => %w('ennusālet 'ennusālta 'ennusālše 'ennusāl 'ennusālā 'ennusālnā 'ennusāltun 'ennusālšin 'ennusālū),
              :imperfect   => %w('ennusuol 'ennusuolat 'ennusuolaš 'ennusuol 'ennusuolā 'ennusuolan 'ennusuoltun 'ennusuolšin 'ennusuolū),
              :subjunctive => %w(vannusāl vatinnusāl vatinnusāl vēnnusāl vēnnusāl vaninnusāl vatinnusāl vatinnusāl vēnnusāl),
              :imperative  => nil,
              :infinitive  => "mannusāl",
              :participle  => "munnasūl" }
  = render 'full_conjugation_table', :title => "Scale III Conjugation", :verb => { :ala => "'ennusāl", :eng => "be lent" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

= section "Quadriconsonantal Roots and 'ennuktāb" do
