= section "Weak Roots in Scale III" do
  = section "C1 = Ř" do
    %p Root-initial *Ř is completely regular. One example is the root *řlīb “milk” (cf. Scale I #{t "ρ̄άλαβ", "řalab"} “give milk”), giving the verbs #{t "αρ̄λήβ", "'ařlēb"} “milk” and #{t "εννυρ̄λώβ", "'ennuřlāb"} “be milked”.

  = section "C2 = Ř" do
    %p Medial *Ř is also completely regular. Once example is the root *břāṯ “mix, agitate”, giving the verbs #{t "αβρ̄ήθ", "'abřēṯ"} “anger” and #{t "εννυβρ̄ώθ", "'ennubřāṯ"} “be angered”.

  = section "C3 = Ř" do
    %p The effects of root-final *Ř are the same as in other scales, and only affect the feminine suffix *-ī in the present tense and imperative, and the vowels of the active participle. The root *ftāř “open” may serve as an example, giving the Scale III verbs #{t "αφτήρ̄", "'aftēř"} “have someone open, help open, open for business” and #{t "εννυφτώρ̄", "'ennuftāř"} “be opened for business”.
    %p In the present tense of both <i>'aktēb</i> and <i>'ennuktāb</i> and the imperative of <i>'aktēb</i>, the feminine marker *-ī is replaced by *ēyi, spelled -ηι: #{t "αφτερ̄ήι", "'afteřēyi"} “have [someone] open! open [for business]! (f)” (not **'afteřī), #{t "ιννυφταρ̄ήι", "yinnuftařēyi"} “it (f) is being opened for business” (not **yinnuftařī).
    %p In addition, the /i/ that immediately precedes C<sub>3</sub> in the active participle is lowered to /e/: #{t "μώατερ̄", "māfteř"} “having open, opening for business” (not **māftiř).

  = section "C1 = '/H" do
    %p Root-initial *' and *H both surface as consonantal /h/, with an epenthetic /a/ inserted immediately afterwards to prevent illegal clusters. Two common examples are the roots *'kāl “eat” and *hbād “work”, giving the Scale III verbs #{t "αηακήλ", "'ahakēl"} “feed”, #{t "εννυηακώλ", "'ennuhakāl"} “be fed”, #{t "αηαβήδ", "'ahabēd"} “employ”, and #{t "εννυηαβώδ", "'ennuhabād"} “be employed”: #{t "αηακιήλετ", "'ahakielet"} “you (m) were being fed” (not **'a'kielet), #{t "αννυηαβώδ", "'annuhabād"} “I am employed” (not **'annuhbād).
    %p For the purposes of assigning stress, the epenthetic /a/ is ignored. Thus, the perfective subjunctive form #{t "в̄ατίννυηαβαδ", "vatinnuhabad"} “[that] you were employed” is stressed on the syllable *-tin- rather than *-nu-, even though the former is now four syllables from the end of the word.

  = section "C2 = '/H" do
    %p Medial *' and *H assimilate into the preceding #{template "C1"}, causing gemination or aspiration. The root *fhāl “make, do, use”, for instance, becomes #{t "αφφήλ", "'affēl"} “turn on [a device, etc.], enforce [a rule, etc.]” and #{t "εννυφφώλ", "'ennuffāl"} “be turned on, be enforced”. Shown below are the present and preterite of #{t "αφφήλ", "'affēl"}:
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = %w(ωφφήλ τωφφήλ τωφφελεί ιωφφήλ ιωφφελεί νωφφελού τωφφελού τωφφελού ιωφφελού ιωφφελού)
        - latin = %w('āffēl tāffēl tāffelī yāffēl yāffelī nāffelū tāffelū tāffelū yāffelū yāffelū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Present Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'affēl", :eng => "turn on, enforce" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
        - alashian = %w(αφφήλετ αφφήλτα αφφήλσ̄ε αφφήλ αφφηλώ αφφηλνώ αφφήλτυν αφφήλσ̄ιν αφφηλού αφφηλού)
        - latin = %w('affēlet 'affēlta 'affēlše 'affēl 'affēlā 'affēlnā 'affēltun 'affēlšin 'affēlū 'affēlū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Preterite Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'affēl", :eng => "turn on, enforce" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "C3 = '" do
    %p As elsewhere, root-final *' behaves erratically. The root *ldā' “go up, rise” gives the verbs #{t "αλδή", "'aldē"} “lift up, pull up” and #{t "εννυλδώ", "'ennuldā"} “be lifted up, be pulled up”.
    %p In the present tense, the glottal stop drops when word-final and is present elsewhere:
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = %w(ωλδή τωλδή τωλδεεί ιωλδή ιωλδεεί νωλδεού τωλδεού τωλδεού ιωλδεού ιωλδεού)
        - latin = %w('āldē tāldē tālde'ī yāldē' yālde'ī nālde'ū tālde'ū tālde'ū yālde'ū yālde'ū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Present Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'aldē", :eng => "lift up" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
        - alashian = %w(αννυλδώ τιννυλδώ τιννυλδαεί ιννυλδώ ιννυλδαεί νιννυλδαού τιννυλδαού τιννυλδαού ιννυλδαού ιννυλδαού)
        - latin = %w('annuldā tinnuldā tinnulda'ī yinnuldā yinnulda'ī ninnulda'ū tinnulda'ū tinnulda'ū yinnulda'ū yinnulda'ū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Present Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'ennuldā", :eng => "be lifted up" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
    %p The preterite features the special set of aspirated suffixes rather than the normal set. The glottal stop disappears in all forms other than the third person singular feminine and third person plural. Additional contraction takes place in the first person singular:
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = %w(αλδήτ αλδήττα αλδήτζζε αλδή αλδηώ αλδηννώ αλδήττυν αλδήτζζιν αλδηού αλδηού)
        - latin = %w('aldēt 'aldētha 'aldēčhe 'aldē 'aldē'ā 'aldēnnā 'aldēthun 'aldēčhin 'aldē'ū 'aldē'ū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Preterite Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'aldē", :eng => "lift up" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
        - alashian = %w(εννυλδώτ εννυλδώττα εννυλδώτζζε εννυλδώ εννυλδωώ εννυλδωννώ εννυλδώττυν εννυλδώτζζιν εννυλωού εννυλδωού)
        - latin = %w('ennuldāt 'ennuldātha 'ennuldāčhe 'ennuldā 'ennuldā'ā 'ennuldānnā 'ennuldāthun 'ennuldāčhin 'ennuldā'ū 'ennuldā'ū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Preterite Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'ennuldā", :eng => "be lifted up" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
    %p In the imperfect the glottal stop also drops in all forms other than the third person singular feminine and third person plural. The sequences -ie'e- (<i>'aktēb</i>) and -uo'a- (<i>'ennuktāb</i>) contract to just -ie- and -uo-. The second person plural forms continue to use an aspirated ending.
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = %w(αλδιή αλδιήτ αλδιής̄ αλδιή αλδιηώ αλδιήν αλδιήττυν αλδιήτζζιν αλδιηού αλδιηού)
        - latin = %w('aldie 'aldiet 'aldieš 'aldie 'aldie'ā 'aldien 'aldiethun 'aldiečhin 'aldie'ū 'aldie'ū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Imperfect Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'aldē", :eng => "lift up" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
        - alashian = %w(εννυλδυώ εννυλδυώτ εννυλδυώς̄ εννυλδυώ εννυλδυωώ εννυλδυών εννυλδυώττυν εννυλδυώτζζιν εννυλδυωού εννυλδυωού)
        - latin = %w('ennulduo 'ennulduot 'ennulduoš 'ennulduo 'ennulduo'ā 'ennulduon 'ennulduothun 'ennulduočhin 'ennulduo'ū 'ennulduo'ū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Imperfect Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'ennuldā", :eng => "be lifted up" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
    %p The glottal stop simply drops in the perfective subjunctive:
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = %w(в̄ώλδε в̄ατώλδε в̄ιώλδε в̄ανώλδε в̄ατώλδε в̄ιώλδε)
        - latin = %w(vālde vatālde vyālde vanālde vatālde vyālde)
        %td= render 'subjunctive_table', :title => "Scale III Perfective Subjunctive", :verb => { :ala => "'aldē", :eng => "lift up" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
        - alashian = %w(в̄άννυλδα в̄ατίννυλδα в̄ήννυλδα в̄ανίννυλδα в̄ατίννυλδα в̄ήννυλδα)
        - latin = %w(vannulda vatinnulda vēnnulda vaninnulda vatinnulda vēnnulda)
        %td= render 'subjunctive_table', :title => "Scale III Perfective Subjunctive", :verb => { :ala => "'ennuldā", :eng => "be lifted up" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
    %p The typical imperative works as expected: the glottal stop drops in the masculine singular (when word-final), and remains in the other forms. In the s-imperative, the glottal stop drops in all forms and causes #{template "C2"} gemination/aspiration in the feminine singular and plural forms:
    - alashian = %w(ισλεδή ισλεδδεί ισλεδδού ισλεδδού)
    - latin = %w('isledē 'isleddī 'isleddū 'isleddū)
    = render 'imperative_table', :title => "Scale III Imperative", :verb => { :ala => "'aldē", :eng => "lift up" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
    %p The deverbatives simply lose the glottal stop:
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = [ { :name => "Infinitive", :ala => "μωλδή", :lat => "māldē", :meaning => "lift up" },
                       { :name => "Active Part.", :ala => "μώλδι", :lat => "māldi", :meaning => "lifting up" } ]
        %td= render 'deverbative_table', :title => "Scale III Deverbatives", :verb => { :ala => "'aldē", :eng => "lift up" }, :forms => alashian
        - alashian = [ { :name => "Infinitive", :ala => "μαννυλδώ", :lat => "mannuldā", :meaning => "be lifted up" },
                       { :name => "Passive Part.", :ala => "μύνναλδα", :lat => "munnalda", :meaning => "being lifted up" } ]
        %td= render 'deverbative_table', :title => "Scale III Deverbatives", :verb => { :ala => "'ennuldā", :eng => "be lifted up" }, :forms => alashian

  = section "C3 = H" do
    %p Roots with final *H lose this radical and conjugate as though they were biconsonantal. The root *mnāh “forbid”, for instance, behaves as though it were *mVn (the vowel is unrecoverable), giving the verbs #{t "αμήν", "'amēn"} “contest, dispute” and #{t "εννυμών", "'ennumān"} “be contested, be disputed”. These then follow a regular biconsonantal paradigm.

  = section "C1 = Y/W" do
    %p Initial *Y and *W simply merge into the preceding vowel according to some relatively straightforward rules:
    %ul
      %li *ay → ē, *aw → ū
      %li *uy → ū, *uw → ū
      %li *āy → ā, *āw → ā
    %p This applies for roots such as *ymīn “right”, yielding the verbs #{t "ημήν", "'ēmēn"} “direct to the right” and #{t "εννουμών", "'ennūmān"} “be directed to the right”, and *wtīr “stay, remain”, yielding #{t "ουτήρ", "'ūtēr"} “have left over” and #{t "εννουτώρ", "'ennūtār"} “remain left over, be in excess”. The following tables show the present tense and preterite of the two active verbs (though *ymīn has root final *N in addition, resulting in irregular preterite endings):
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = %w(ωμήν τωμήν τωμενεί ιωμήν ιωμενεί νωμενού τωμενού τωμενού ιωμενού ιωμενού)
        - latin = %w('āmēn tāmēn tāmenī yāmēn yāmenī nāmenū tāmenū tāmenū yāmenū yāmenū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Present Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'ēmēn", :eng => "direct right" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
        - alashian = %w(ωτήρ τωτήρ τωτερεί ιωτήρ ιωτερεί νωτερού τωτερού τωτερού ιωτερού ιωτερού)
        - latin = %w('ātēr tātēr tāterī yātēr yāterī nāterū tāterū tāterū yāterū yāterū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Present Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'ūtēr", :eng => "have left over" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
      %tr
        - alashian = %w(ημήνετ ημήττα ημήτζζε ημήν ημηνώ ημηννώ ημήττυν ημήτζζιν ημηνού ημηνού)
        - latin = %w('ēmēnet 'ēmētha 'ēmēčhe 'ēmēn 'ēmēnā 'ēmēnnā 'ēmēthun 'ēmēčhin 'ēmēnū 'ēmēnū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Preterite Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'ēmēn", :eng => "direct right" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
        - alashian = %w(ουτήρετ ουτήρτα ουτήρσ̄ε ουτήρ ουτηρώ ουτηρνώ ουτήρτυν ουτήρσ̄ιν ουτηρού ουτηρού)
        - latin = %w('ūtēret 'ūtērta 'ūtērše 'ūtēr 'ūtērā 'ūtērnā 'ūtērtun 'ūtēršin 'ūtērū 'ūtērū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Preterite Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'ūtēr", :eng => "have left over" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "C3 = Y/W" do
    %p Root-final *Y and *W are simpler to conjugate in Scale III than in Scales I or II. These consonants are preserved when intervocalic, and are lost in all other positions with no change to neighboring vowels. Consider, for instance, the preterite tense forms of the verbs #{t "αβνή", "'abnē"} “have build, help build” (*bnāy “build”) and #{t "αμνή", "'amnē"} “have count, help count” (*mnāw “count”):
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = %w(αβνήιετ αβνήτα αβνήσ̄ε αβνή αβνηιώ αβνηνώ αβνήτυν αβνήσ̄ιν αβνηιού αβνηιού)
        - latin = %w('abnēyet 'abnēta 'abnēše 'abnē 'abnēyā 'abnēnā 'abnētun 'abnēšin 'abnēyū 'abnēyū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Preterite Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'abnē", :eng => "have build" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
        - alashian = %w(αμνήυετ αμνήτα αμνήσ̄ε αμνή αμνηυώ αμνηνώ αμνήτυν αμνήσ̄ιν αμνηυού αμνηυού)
        - latin = %w('amnēwet 'amnēta 'amnēše 'amnē 'amnēwā 'amnēnā 'amnētun 'amnēšin 'amnēwū 'amnēwū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale III Preterite Tense", :verb => { :ala => "'amnē", :eng => "have count" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
    %p The one exception to this pattern are the participles. In the active <i>'aktēb</i> participle, both *Y and *W drop with compensatory lengthening: #{t "μώβνει", "mābnī"} “having build”, #{t "μώμνει", "māmnī"} “having count” (not **mābniy, **māmniw). In the passive <i>'ennuktāb</i> participle, monophthongization takes place: #{t "μύνναβνη", "munnabnē"} “being made to build”, #{t "μύνναμνού", "munnamnū"} “being made to count” (not **munnabnay, **munnamnaw). Note that the new long vowels do not draw the stress.

  = section "C1/C2/C3 = N" do
    %p Roots with initial *N (as in *nkīr “recognize”, giving #{t "ακκήρ", "'əkhēr"} “introduce” and #{t "εννακκώρ", "'ennəkhār"} “be introduced”) undergo assimilation in all forms, with #{template "C2"} being geminated or aspirated. They are otherwise regular, although if aspiration appears, it will be accompanied by vowel reduction.
    %p Roots with medial *N (as in *knās “gather”, giving #{t "ακνής", "'aknēs"} “insert” and #{t "εννυκνώς", "'ennuknās"} “be inserted”#{footnote}) are regular.
    %p Root-final *N is irregular only in the two past tenses, where assimilation takes place in a number of forms. With the root *šfān “cover” we get the verbs #{t "ασ̄φήν", "'ašfēn"} “tell a secret, make someone swear to secrecy” and #{t "εννυσ̄φών", "'ennušfān"} “swear to secrecy”:
