    %p Roots with initial aspirates are largely unproblematic. Since #{template "C1"} is always in a cluster, it will always surface in an unaspirated state. The only difference between this and the regular paradigms is that any short vowel immediately preceding #{template "C1"} will reduce to /ə/; in <i>'aktēb</i> this is not even noticeable orthographically, though the reduction is clear in <i>'ennuktāb</i>. One such root is *thrād, yielding the Scale III verbs #{t "ατρήδ", "'ətrēd"} “send quickly” and #{t "εννατρώδ", "'ennətrād"} “be sent quickly”.

  = section "C2 = PH/TH/KH/TSH/ČH" do
    %p Root-internal aspirates are completely regular, always surface in an unaspirated form, and never show any vowel reduction. For instance, the root *lkhīn “kiss” becomes #{t "αλκήν", "'alkēn"} “touch [something to something], place in contact” and #{t "εννυλκών", "'ennulkān"} “be touched [to], be placed in contact, lie tangent to”.

